<script>
const POSTS = [
  { id:0, title:"Why I Founded The Street Health Project", cat:"Community", excerpt:"Starting a nonprofit as a high school sophomore sounds impossible ‚Äî until the need becomes undeniable.", time:"5 min read", date:"October 2025", emoji:"üè•", vis:"bcv-1", featured:true,
    body:`When I started volunteering at St. Luke's Hospital in the summer of 2025, I expected to feel inspired. What I didn't expect was to come home from every shift thinking: this isn't enough.

I kept noticing the same thing ‚Äî healthcare access doesn't start in a hospital. It starts with something as basic as a toothbrush. A bar of soap. A bandage. For people living without stable housing in the Cedar Rapids area, even these things are out of reach.

I started researching local resources. There weren't many specifically targeted at hygiene and basic healthcare supplies for people experiencing homelessness. So I decided to create something.

The Street Health Project started in October 2025 as a simple idea: assemble kits with healthcare and hygiene essentials, and get them into the hands of people who need them. I began reaching out to local clinics and businesses ‚Äî cold emails, in-person visits, social media posts. Within a few weeks I had secured $200 in donated supplies.

It hasn't been easy. Running an organization at 15 while keeping up with AP Biology, HOSA, and robotics means most evenings look like a juggling act. But every kit that goes out feels like proof that you don't need to wait until you're older, or have more resources, or have more experience. You can start now.

