    body:`Two hundred emails. Between fundraising for HOSA, outreach for the robotics team, and launching The Street Health Project, I've written cold emails to over 200 companies, clinics, and local businesses over the past year.

Most people assume cold emailing doesn't work ‚Äî especially when you're a high schooler asking for money or supplies. But I've gotten enough responses, donations, and partnerships through cold email to know it's worth doing right.

The subject line is everything. If someone doesn't open your email, nothing else matters. The more specific and human, the better.

Don't start with yourself. The biggest mistake is opening with "My name is X and I'm a student at Y." Nobody cares yet. Start with the problem you're solving, or a quick reason why this email is relevant to them specifically.

Personalization beats templates, but don't over-personalize. I write a strong base email and customize the first 1‚Äì2 sentences for each recipient.

Follow-up is where most wins happen. About 60% of the responses I've gotten came after a follow-up, not the initial email. Wait 5‚Äì7 business days, then send a short, friendly check-in.

Track everything. I use a simple spreadsheet: who I emailed, when, what response I got, whether I followed up.

Cold emailing has gotten me supplies for The Street Health Project, sponsors for HOSA, and new community partnerships for robotics. The rejection rate is high. But sometimes one yes changes everything.` },
